  "text": "## Apache Kafka SASL Broker-Side Authentication Implementation\n\n### Overview\nThe SASL broker-side authentication in Apache Kafka is implemented through a sophisticated system of classes that handle mechanism selection, server-side SASL protocol execution, and credential validation. The implementation supports multiple mechanisms: PLAIN, SCRAM (SHA-256/512), GSSAPI (Kerberos), and OAuthBearer.\n\n### Core Authentication Flow\n\n**SaslServerAuthenticator** (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/security/authenticator/SaslServerAuthenticator.java) is the central class implementing the Authenticator interface. It manages the entire broker-side SASL authentication lifecycle with defined state transitions:\n- **INITIAL_REQUEST**: Initial state, expecting either ApiVersions or SaslHandshake request\n- **HANDSHAKE_OR_VERSIONS_REQUEST**: Can accept either ApiVersions or SaslHandshake\n- **HANDSHAKE_REQUEST**: After ApiVersions, must receive SaslHandshake\n- **AUTHENTICATE**: Authentication token exchange phase\n- **COMPLETE**: Authentication succeeded\n- **FAILED**: Authentication failed\n- **REAUTH_PROCESS_HANDSHAKE**: Re-authentication initiation state\n\nThe authenticate() method processes client requests through handleKafkaRequest() for initial handshake, then handleSaslToken() for authentication tokens.\n\n### Mechanism Selection and Creation\n\n**SaslChannelBuilder** (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/network/SaslChannelBuilder.java) is responsible for configuring and selecting the appropriate callback handlers based on enabled SASL mechanisms. The createServerCallbackHandlers() method instantiates mechanism-specific handlers:\n\n1. **PLAIN**: PlainServerCallbackHandler (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/security/plain/internals/PlainServerCallbackHandler.java)\n2. **SCRAM**: ScramServerCallbackHandler (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/security/scram/internals/ScramServerCallbackHandler.java)\n3. **GSSAPI**: SaslServerCallbackHandler (default for Kerberos)\n4. **OAuthBearer**: OAuthBearerUnsecuredValidatorCallbackHandler (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/security/oauthbearer/internals/unsecured/OAuthBearerUnsecuredValidatorCallbackHandler.java)\n\nThe handleHandshakeRequest() method in SaslServerAuthenticator validates the client-selected mechanism against the enabled mechanisms list and returns the list of supported mechanisms if validation fails.\n\n### Mechanism-Specific Implementations\n\n**PLAIN Mechanism**:\n- PlainSaslServer (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/security/plain/internals/PlainSaslServer.java): Implements SaslServer for PLAIN authentication\n- PlainLoginModule (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/security/plain/PlainLoginModule.java): JAAS login module for PLAIN\n- PlainServerCallbackHandler: Handles username/password validation callbacks\n\n**SCRAM Mechanisms** (SCRAM-SHA-256, SCRAM-SHA-512):\n- ScramSaslServer (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/security/scram/internals/ScramSaslServer.java): Implements SaslServer for SCRAM authentication with salted password generation and multi-round authentication\n- ScramServerCallbackHandler: Manages credential cache lookups for SCRAM credentials\n- ScramLoginModule (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/security/scram/ScramLoginModule.java): JAAS login module for SCRAM\n- ScramMechanism (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/security/scram/internals/ScramMechanism.java): Enum defining SCRAM mechanism variants and properties\n\n**GSSAPI (Kerberos)**:\n- Handled through standard Java GSS/SASL framework via Sasl.createSaslServer()\n- createSaslKerberosServer() in SaslServerAuthenticator extracts service principal and hostname from broker's Kerberos subject\n- KerberosClientCallbackHandler (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/security/kerberos/KerberosClientCallbackHandler.java): Client-side handler\n- KerberosLogin (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/security/kerberos/KerberosLogin.java): Manages Kerberos login context\n\n**OAuthBearer**:\n- OAuthBearerSaslServer (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/security/oauthbearer/internals/OAuthBearerSaslServer.java): Implements SaslServer for OAuthBearer token validation\n- OAuthBearerLoginModule (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/security/oauthbearer/OAuthBearerLoginModule.java): JAAS login module\n- OAuthBearerUnsecuredValidatorCallbackHandler: Validates bearer tokens (unsecured variant)\n\n### Authentication Context Lifecycle\n\n**SaslAuthenticationContext** (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/security/auth/SaslAuthenticationContext.java) encapsulates the authentication context passed to the principal builder. It holds:\n- The SaslServer instance managing the authentication state\n- Security protocol (SASL_SSL or SASL_PLAINTEXT)\n- Client's InetAddress\n- Listener name\n- Optional SSL session (for SASL_SSL)\n\nThe principal() method in SaslServerAuthenticator creates a SaslAuthenticationContext and passes it to the KafkaPrincipalBuilder, which extracts the authenticated principal from the SaslServer based on mechanism-specific properties.\n\n### Credential Management\n\n**CredentialCache** (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/security/authenticator/CredentialCache.java) manages credentials for SCRAM mechanisms, providing credential lookups for verification during SCRAM authentication.\n\n### Configuration and Constants\n\n- **SaslConfigs** (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/config/SaslConfigs.java): Defines SASL configuration properties like SASL_MECHANISM, SASL_JAAS_CONFIG, SASL_CLIENT_CALLBACK_HANDLER_CLASS\n- **BrokerSecurityConfigs** (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/config/internals/BrokerSecurityConfigs.java): Broker-specific configs like SASL_ENABLED_MECHANISMS_CONFIG, SASL_SERVER_CALLBACK_HANDLER_CLASS_CONFIG, CONNECTIONS_MAX_REAUTH_MS_CONFIG\n- **SaslInternalConfigs** (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/security/authenticator/SaslInternalConfigs.java): Internal configuration constants for session lifetime management\n\n### Protocol Messages\n\n- **SaslHandshakeRequest/Response** (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/requests/SaslHandshakeRequest.java and Response.java): Mechanism negotiation\n- **SaslAuthenticateRequest/Response** (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/requests/SaslAuthenticateRequest.java and Response.java): Authentication token exchange (KIP-43 compatible)\n\n### Supporting Classes\n\n- **SaslAuthenticationException** (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/errors/SaslAuthenticationException.java): SASL-specific authentication failures\n- **SaslExtensions/SaslExtensionsCallback**: Mechanism-specific extensions support\n- **ScramExtensions/ScramCredential**: SCRAM-specific credential and extension handling\n- **DefaultKafkaPrincipalBuilder**: Builds KafkaPrincipal from SaslAuthenticationContext\n\n### Mechanism Selection Logic\n\nThe mechanism selection occurs in handleHandshakeRequest() of SaslServerAuthenticator:\n1. Client sends SaslHandshakeRequest with preferred mechanism\n2. Server checks if mechanism is in enabledMechanisms list (from BrokerSecurityConfigs.SASL_ENABLED_MECHANISMS_CONFIG)\n3. If supported, server sends SaslHandshakeResponse with Errors.NONE and list of enabled mechanisms\n4. If not supported, server sends error response with all enabled mechanisms\n5. createSaslServer() is called with the validated mechanism, which:\n   - For GSSAPI: Calls createSaslKerberosServer() for Kerberos-specific setup\n   - For others: Uses Java's Sasl.createSaslServer() with the appropriate callback handler\n\n### Re-authentication Support\n\nSaslServerAuthenticator supports connection re-authentication through reauthenticate() method with re-authentication states (REAUTH_PROCESS_HANDSHAKE, REAUTH_BAD_MECHANISM) to ensure the same mechanism is used for re-authentication.\n"
}

